1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,360
I'm Jake O'Neill, creator of Animographs, and this is how a Formula One race car works.

2
00:00:13,680 --> 00:00:19,840
Let's start with aerodynamics, which is how the car interacts with and moves through the air

3
00:00:19,840 --> 00:00:27,920
around it. It's best to focus on overall theory here to avoid getting lost in the absolute maze

4
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:35,200
of individual aerodynamic features. The front wing curves upward, forcing air to move around it

5
00:00:35,200 --> 00:00:41,040
in such a way that a high-pressure area forms above the wing with lower pressure beneath.

6
00:00:42,960 --> 00:00:48,160
This pressure difference contributes to a kind of suction force called downforce

7
00:00:48,880 --> 00:00:51,280
that pushes or sticks the car to the track.

8
00:00:51,920 --> 00:00:59,200
Where the wing ends and these different pressure zones meet, the air crashes into itself,

9
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:01,760
creating a spiraling vortex.

10
00:01:03,920 --> 00:01:11,040
Vortices cause drag, which tugs at the car, slowing it down. A cap on the wing tip

11
00:01:11,040 --> 00:01:14,640
interrupts vortex formation for a less intense effect.

12
00:01:14,960 --> 00:01:22,480
In contrast, the pointed, curved end surfaces on the inside edge of the wing intentionally shape

13
00:01:22,480 --> 00:01:28,720
and directive vortex around the floor of the car, sealing in the clean air that passes beneath.

14
00:01:31,760 --> 00:01:38,800
So, while vortices do cause drag, they're also a useful tool to separate and seal in different

15
00:01:39,680 --> 00:01:47,040
areas of airflow. As a matter of tradition, F1 cars don't have fenders, and the open,

16
00:01:47,040 --> 00:01:52,400
spinning wheel and tire combination is a major source of dirty turbulent air.

17
00:01:55,200 --> 00:02:00,320
Turbulent air is unpredictable and not very useful for aerodynamic goals,

18
00:02:00,880 --> 00:02:08,160
like generating downforce. Directly behind the tires, the bargeboards condition or clean up

19
00:02:08,160 --> 00:02:13,520
some of this airflow, while also pushing lots of dirty air away from the body.

20
00:02:20,160 --> 00:02:26,080
The narrow gap between the car floor and the track turns the entire floor into a giant

21
00:02:26,080 --> 00:02:33,040
downforce generator, as air squeezes, thins, and rushes beneath the car at a different rate

22
00:02:33,040 --> 00:02:41,280
and pressure than overhead air. The floor has a forward tilt or rake that creates very low

23
00:02:41,280 --> 00:02:46,880
pressure at its narrowest point, but allows air to more smoothly rejoin ambient air pressure as

24
00:02:46,880 --> 00:02:54,000
it flows out the back. A diffuser at the rear amplifies this goal, with its more pronounced

25
00:02:54,000 --> 00:03:00,800
upward curvature. The diffuser has vertical veins to control and direct the massive vortices that

26
00:03:00,800 --> 00:03:04,320
form behind the car, as air pours out from underneath.

27
00:03:10,480 --> 00:03:16,880
Clean air is directed into the side pods for cooling purposes. This stream passes through

28
00:03:16,880 --> 00:03:23,840
the car and out the back beneath the rear wing. The smoothly contoured body guides

29
00:03:23,840 --> 00:03:28,960
air streams gracefully around bodywork for predictable handling under extreme conditions.

30
00:03:32,960 --> 00:03:37,200
The upward curved rear wing, which is another critical downforce generator,

31
00:03:37,920 --> 00:03:43,760
has notched end caps with gaps and louvers to allow some air to combine early,

32
00:03:44,400 --> 00:03:50,800
altering and shaping rear wing vortex characteristics. It's also where in wet conditions,

33
00:03:50,800 --> 00:03:55,440
the noticeable misty wing tip vortices sometimes appear in plain sight.

34
00:03:59,920 --> 00:04:05,200
A hydraulic actuator tilts a section of the rear wing when the drag reduction system or

35
00:04:05,200 --> 00:04:11,840
DRS is engaged, generating less rear downforce, but allowing higher overall speed.

36
00:04:11,840 --> 00:04:21,760
The massive area of dirty air behind the car can make it difficult for other cars to approach

37
00:04:21,760 --> 00:04:28,320
and overtake. It's worth noting here that in coming years, the aerodynamic design regulations

38
00:04:28,320 --> 00:04:34,240
for F1 cars are set for major changes to encourage closer racing and overtaking.

39
00:04:34,800 --> 00:04:40,320
The airflow pattern might look more like this than the current wide dirty wake.

40
00:04:42,320 --> 00:04:49,120
Now let's go underneath this exterior bodywork, starting with the core support structure.

41
00:04:51,600 --> 00:04:59,520
A carbon fiber shell called a monocock. The engine heads and block and the gearbox enclosure

42
00:04:59,520 --> 00:05:06,400
form the main structural support for all other systems. There's no additional frame or chassis

43
00:05:06,480 --> 00:05:12,320
underneath.

44
00:05:19,200 --> 00:05:19,920
Suspension.

45
00:05:22,160 --> 00:05:27,440
Both front and back suspension setups share similar components, upper and lower

46
00:05:27,440 --> 00:05:34,080
wishbone arms with a push or pole rod. The wishbones are rigid structural supports

47
00:05:34,080 --> 00:05:39,040
with limited vertical travel. At the front where heat isn't an issue,

48
00:05:39,680 --> 00:05:46,080
wishbones are directly attached to the monocock and have simple flexure joints designed to bend

49
00:05:46,080 --> 00:05:53,280
under load. At the rear where engine heat can be intense, spherical bearings are used.

50
00:05:56,480 --> 00:06:03,520
The push or pole rod is where the action happens. Our model has push rods in the front and pull

51
00:06:03,520 --> 00:06:07,840
rods in the back, which simplified just indicates how the system is mounted,

52
00:06:08,560 --> 00:06:14,800
to push or pull connected suspension parts. If parts can be mounted down low for a lower

53
00:06:14,800 --> 00:06:21,360
center of gravity, all the better. The pull rod connects to a rocker and damper,

54
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:28,320
which we call shock absorbers in normal cars. But instead of large coiled springs,

55
00:06:28,960 --> 00:06:34,640
F1 suspension uses a small metal rod called a torsion bar that twists under load.

56
00:06:35,840 --> 00:06:42,320
One side of the torsion bar moves with the outer cylindrical shaft, while the other side is stationary.

57
00:06:47,680 --> 00:06:54,000
Both independent suspension sides are linked to a central roll bar that twists to limit body roll.

58
00:06:59,200 --> 00:07:05,680
Heave is the vertical position of the car, which is critically important for proper aerodynamics.

59
00:07:06,960 --> 00:07:13,200
The heave spring and damper cleverly come into play when both sides move up or down together,

60
00:07:13,200 --> 00:07:20,080
for example, during acceleration or braking, but are mostly inactive for other movements.

61
00:07:21,840 --> 00:07:27,120
The heave spring in our model is a stack of flexible, cone shaped washers that compress

62
00:07:27,120 --> 00:07:34,400
together under load. Washes can be added or subtracted for fine adjustments.

63
00:07:43,840 --> 00:07:48,080
The front suspension handles similar tasks to the rear but with different techniques.

64
00:07:52,800 --> 00:07:56,320
The steering system is closely packaged with front suspension.

65
00:07:57,360 --> 00:08:03,120
A track rod links each tire to a fairly standard hydraulic rack and pinion setup,

66
00:08:03,840 --> 00:08:06,320
with the steering column extending into the cockpit.

67
00:08:07,760 --> 00:08:12,560
The rear suspension has a track rod as well for vertical tire angle adjustment.

68
00:08:19,520 --> 00:08:25,440
All wheels must be attached to the car with wheel tethers. These are strong cables that keep

69
00:08:25,440 --> 00:08:30,960
wheels connected to the car in the event of an accident. They're required to pass through

70
00:08:30,960 --> 00:08:39,840
more than one suspension element for increased safety. With few exceptions, most exposed suspension

71
00:08:39,840 --> 00:08:45,600
elements are either made from or bonded with carbon fiber for better aerodynamic forms.

72
00:08:47,040 --> 00:08:53,680
This is another major reason suspension parts are packaged inside bodywork away from outside air

73
00:08:53,680 --> 00:08:58,000
wherever possible. Breaking System

74
00:09:02,720 --> 00:09:07,840
A master cylinder and reservoir controls and stores hydraulic fluid for braking.

75
00:09:09,920 --> 00:09:16,160
F1 cars have two master cylinders and accompanying reservoirs for front and rear brakes respectively.

76
00:09:16,880 --> 00:09:22,880
The cylinders are mounted to the brake pedal on one end and a threaded brake bias screw on the other.

77
00:09:24,560 --> 00:09:29,600
This bias screw is electronically controlled and can be adjusted on the fly as directed by

78
00:09:29,600 --> 00:09:35,600
the driver. The screw position allows different pressure to the front or rear brakes.

79
00:09:37,280 --> 00:09:42,000
Brake lines sneak through suspension elements to the brake caliper and shoe assembly.

80
00:09:43,120 --> 00:09:49,520
Intense brake heat must be precisely managed so the entire inner wheel assembly is covered

81
00:09:49,520 --> 00:09:56,000
by a ducted carbon fiber shroud. The front wing helps direct air into the brake ducts

82
00:09:56,000 --> 00:10:01,760
and through the inner wheel for cooling. The calipers are mounted at the lowest possible

83
00:10:01,760 --> 00:10:08,160
position for proper brake bleed. That is ensuring troublesome air bubbles can escape hydraulic

84
00:10:08,160 --> 00:10:16,720
brake lines while maintaining a low center of gravity. The brake discs and shoes are made from

85
00:10:16,720 --> 00:10:23,840
a carbon-based material. The disc has thousands of small holes extending from the center outwards

86
00:10:23,840 --> 00:10:32,720
from maximum cooling effects. The rear brakes have a similar design strategy that have become

87
00:10:32,720 --> 00:10:38,960
smaller in recent years with the addition of the MGUK or motor generator unit kinetic.

88
00:10:39,760 --> 00:10:47,440
The MGUK is geared to the crankshaft and functions as an electrical power generator

89
00:10:47,440 --> 00:10:52,320
to charge an on-board battery as driven by a portion of rear braking forces.

90
00:10:54,400 --> 00:11:01,360
A computer mounted inside the gearbox enclosure manages and balances this complex braking system.

91
00:11:09,600 --> 00:11:16,560
The wheels are secured to the hub with a single wheel nut.

92
00:11:17,680 --> 00:11:24,080
Metal retention pins keep the nut securely in place. A specially designed wheel gun pushes

93
00:11:24,080 --> 00:11:34,000
these pins down when removing the nut. Engine and associated systems.

94
00:11:39,680 --> 00:11:48,400
F1 cars use six cylinders in a V configuration. The pistons are somewhat flat and small to suit

95
00:11:48,400 --> 00:11:56,800
the high-reving engine. Intricate exhaust headers feed a comparatively massive turbine at the rear

96
00:11:56,800 --> 00:12:02,960
of the engine which is part of a split turbocharger design that separates these normally stacked

97
00:12:03,040 --> 00:12:09,760
turbo components. Red hot exhaust gases drive the turbine wheel

98
00:12:12,640 --> 00:12:18,560
which in turn spins the front mounted compressor wheel drawing in and compressing

99
00:12:18,560 --> 00:12:27,200
huge quantities of air. All this pressure adds unwanted heat to the incoming air

100
00:12:28,000 --> 00:12:35,680
so one entire side pod is dedicated to the intercooler. The path of incoming air looks like this.

101
00:12:36,320 --> 00:12:42,640
The compressor draws air in through an intake duct mounted in the roll hoop above and behind

102
00:12:42,640 --> 00:12:52,240
the driver's head. Hot air leaves the compressor towards the intercooler. Side pod air rushes by

103
00:12:52,240 --> 00:12:56,560
the intercoolers tubes and fins cooling the compressor air inside.

104
00:13:00,960 --> 00:13:07,200
The now cooled air passes through the special split ducting that feeds separate intake plenums.

105
00:13:09,120 --> 00:13:14,080
These are chambers designed to keep air pressure balanced between cylinders.

106
00:13:14,400 --> 00:13:24,000
Intake trumpets extend into the plenums for specially tuned air delivery to each cylinder.

107
00:13:28,800 --> 00:13:34,480
The side pod air flows by and cools the engine and other internal parts on its way out the back

108
00:13:34,480 --> 00:13:43,520
of the car. The exhaust section of the turbo has dual waste gates corresponding to each

109
00:13:43,520 --> 00:13:50,400
exhaust input. To vent off excess gases when needed, waste gate pipes follow the main exhaust

110
00:13:50,400 --> 00:13:58,640
pipe out the back. A high-tech heat recovery unit sits between these turbo compartments

111
00:13:58,640 --> 00:14:08,400
called the MGUH or motor generator unit heat. Excess heat from turbo gases drives this unit

112
00:14:08,400 --> 00:14:16,400
to act as an electric generator to charge the onboard battery. Energy recovery system.

113
00:14:19,520 --> 00:14:27,200
The MGUH and the previously shown MGUK together make up the hybrid functionality of the modern F1

114
00:14:27,200 --> 00:14:34,480
car. Both units generate electrical charge for the battery. Once sufficiently charged,

115
00:14:34,480 --> 00:14:40,800
the battery can send power back through the MGUK unit, which again is geared to the crankshaft.

116
00:14:41,840 --> 00:14:50,240
In this way, the MGUK can generate an additional maximum 160 horsepower or as much as a small

117
00:14:50,240 --> 00:15:01,360
separate car engine. Cooling. Various additional radiators for cooling occupy the opposing side pod.

118
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:10,400
This includes the main engine cooling radiator, an oil cooler, and a battery cooler. An additional

119
00:15:10,400 --> 00:15:17,680
bank of radiators sits in the path of a separate roll hoop air duct to cool hydraulic oil, gearbox

120
00:15:17,680 --> 00:15:25,600
oil, and the MGUH and K-systems. F1 teams may locate specific radiators in different positions

121
00:15:25,600 --> 00:15:32,240
than I've shown here, though the general available spaces will be similar. They may also use water

122
00:15:32,240 --> 00:15:38,080
driven intercooling for turbo air, in contrast to the simpler air-to-air setup I've chosen.

123
00:15:39,440 --> 00:15:48,320
Fuel tank. The fuel tank, also called a fuel cell, is a nearly puncture-proof Kevlar bladder

124
00:15:48,320 --> 00:15:54,800
lined with rubber. It occupies an isolated compartment in the carbon fiber monocoque

125
00:15:54,800 --> 00:16:04,240
shell and fills all available space. F1 fuel cells can hold an incredible 30 to 40 gallons

126
00:16:04,240 --> 00:16:10,560
of fuel, which is just enough for a single race as pit stop refueling is not allowed.

127
00:16:10,880 --> 00:16:19,440
These cars get an estimated 4 to 6 miles per gallon of fuel. The tank has various internal

128
00:16:19,440 --> 00:16:26,400
baffles with one-way valves to tame the sloshing liquid under incredible racing forces. The goal

129
00:16:26,400 --> 00:16:32,960
is to keep the large fuel mass centered and low, and also to prevent foaming and fuel pump starvation.

130
00:16:33,520 --> 00:16:38,880
The engine oil tank is placed between the engine and fuel cell.

131
00:16:41,840 --> 00:16:50,240
Gearbox. The 8-speed gearbox, 7-forward plus one reverse, sits behind the engine in its own

132
00:16:50,240 --> 00:16:57,440
aluminum cartridge. The rear differential gears connect to rear axles with special tripod joints

133
00:16:57,440 --> 00:17:01,120
that allow spinning axles to tilt with the rear suspension movement.

134
00:17:03,680 --> 00:17:12,560
Safety systems. F1 cars have robust safety systems. The rear crash structure protects against rear

135
00:17:12,560 --> 00:17:21,120
impact. Side crash structures are concealed within the aerodynamic bodywork. The removable

136
00:17:21,120 --> 00:17:27,120
front-nose section handles front impact, and the all-important monocoque forms a protective

137
00:17:27,120 --> 00:17:34,880
cocoon around the driver. Also attached to the monocoque, a halo device which was implemented in

138
00:17:34,880 --> 00:17:44,080
2018 for additional driver safety and a roll hoop. The driver's helmet is kept within a specific

139
00:17:44,080 --> 00:17:49,120
angle from the roll hoop to the body, for maximum protection in the event of a rollover.

140
00:17:49,840 --> 00:17:58,640
Cockpit. F1 racing seats are crafted from molds taken from a specific driver's body.

141
00:17:59,360 --> 00:18:06,640
The driver sits in a reclined position, almost like laying semi-upright in a hammock. A six-point

142
00:18:06,640 --> 00:18:13,760
harness keeps the driver in place. The seat wraps around the driver's body wherever possible,

143
00:18:13,760 --> 00:18:21,040
and safety structures surround the helmet area. Drivers wear a special brace,

144
00:18:21,040 --> 00:18:27,280
called the Hans or head and neck device, to limit head movement in adverse conditions.

145
00:18:28,320 --> 00:18:33,520
A connected strap clips to either side of the helmet, and the shoulder harness straps keep the

146
00:18:33,520 --> 00:18:41,120
device pressed against the driver. A drinks tube extends over the shoulder. It's connected to a

147
00:18:41,120 --> 00:18:48,560
small fluid reservoir to keep drivers hydrated while racing. Drivers use different helmet front

148
00:18:48,560 --> 00:18:54,400
and rear spoiler designs to keep their helmets from lifting or moving around with sometimes

149
00:18:54,400 --> 00:19:01,120
dramatically shifting air pressures. In recent years, the visor opening has further narrowed

150
00:19:01,120 --> 00:19:08,160
to protect the more fragile visor area from puncture or breakage. Cockpit design makes

151
00:19:08,160 --> 00:19:14,560
efficient use of all available space, such that drivers must remove the steering wheel to exit the car.

152
00:19:18,000 --> 00:19:26,160
Steering wheel. This is the famed Formula One steering wheel. Drivers mostly don't need to

153
00:19:26,160 --> 00:19:33,280
remove their hands from the wheel for steering, so the wheel doesn't need to be round. A customizable

154
00:19:33,280 --> 00:19:38,960
display at the center shows the current gear as the largest item, along with things like lap

155
00:19:38,960 --> 00:19:46,640
times, tire and brake temperatures, average speed, and so on. The daunting array of knobs,

156
00:19:46,640 --> 00:19:52,880
dials, and LEDs gives drivers and teams fine controls that can be adjusted on the fly during

157
00:19:52,880 --> 00:20:00,240
a race. Clockwise from the upper left, there's the energy recovery system dial to control the

158
00:20:00,240 --> 00:20:08,640
MDU-H and K, left and right menu navigation buttons, a push to talk radio switch for team

159
00:20:08,640 --> 00:20:15,680
communication, LED warning lights for critical systems, a row of LEDs across the top of the

160
00:20:15,680 --> 00:20:22,400
display acts as a rev counter and shift light system, the launch control switch which is turned

161
00:20:22,400 --> 00:20:28,880
on for race starts and off when racing, the brake balance dial for front and rear brake bias,

162
00:20:29,680 --> 00:20:35,200
a pit limits button to automatically impose things like pit lane speed and acceleration

163
00:20:35,200 --> 00:20:40,720
restrictions, an engine mapping dial to alter engine performance characteristics,

164
00:20:41,920 --> 00:20:49,520
DRS toggle button, rear differential lock open or closed adjustment with separate turn entry and

165
00:20:49,520 --> 00:20:57,280
turn exit adjusters, the drinks dispenser button, more settings navigation buttons,

166
00:20:58,080 --> 00:21:06,080
three programmable preset dials for the engine, chassis, or suspension, and a scenario selector

167
00:21:06,080 --> 00:21:13,920
for things like wet weather or tire preservation presets. The neutral button is for neutral and

168
00:21:13,920 --> 00:21:21,280
reverse gears which can't be selected with rear paddle shifters, a message okay button, an overtake

169
00:21:21,360 --> 00:21:27,360
button to instantly apply optimal settings for overtaking, and finally a hydraulic settings

170
00:21:27,360 --> 00:21:32,720
dial to control the complex hydraulic components spread throughout the car, for example in the

171
00:21:32,720 --> 00:21:40,480
gearbox and suspension systems. Paddles at the back of the steering wheel handle gear shifting up or

172
00:21:40,480 --> 00:21:47,760
down, the middle paddles are driver customizable, and both bottom paddles actuate the clutch,

173
00:21:48,720 --> 00:21:55,840
only one clutch paddle can be used for race start, once in motion the clutch isn't needed for gear

174
00:21:55,840 --> 00:22:03,200
shifting, further down into the cockpit we see the gas pedal with contours to wrap around the

175
00:22:03,200 --> 00:22:08,880
driver's foot so as to keep pedals completely separate and the brake pedal on the left,

176
00:22:09,680 --> 00:22:18,480
sensors, there are sensors all over these cars, for example a pilot tube at the front measures air

177
00:22:18,480 --> 00:22:25,360
speed, the driver's custom molded earplugs have an accelerometer to track head movement,

178
00:22:26,400 --> 00:22:30,080
there's a microphone at the rear to pick up exhaust sound,

179
00:22:30,400 --> 00:22:40,640
for size comparison here's our average height driver model standing beside an average sized car

180
00:22:41,680 --> 00:22:43,120
next to our formula model,

181
00:22:49,520 --> 00:22:54,480
it's important to note that even with the level of detail i've strived to attain here,

182
00:22:54,560 --> 00:23:01,360
the complexity in f1 cars feels almost endless in a way that truly tested my research abilities

183
00:23:02,480 --> 00:23:12,080
they really are incredible racing machines

